text: Speaking of, when can we expect another Where Are They Now?
Do those count as staples? I’ve only ever seen Deathless maybe once in a couple of years and never Tusker.
same, but vice versa
Tusker was definitely a staple.
I think it was falling out of favor right around when you got into magic, Henry. Maybe a little before.
Deathless Angel was staple-y. It was $2 for awhile.
Actually, it still is.
maybe the average cmc of staples declines as format popularity increases
as format popularity increases, the set of cards considered staples changes
Tweet back at me. I think this conversation is interesting. And I really am interested to hear what current staples people think are on their way to getting phased out.
as better cards are printed, staple set changes
This is Murica...you don't get to tell me what to do, especially on our birthday! Commie...
I think Mirage Mirror phases out Mimic Vat, and probably some other stuff.
Really? Those seems to be very different pieces of tech
You'll do it and you'll like it, Henry.
Beyond being 3 drops I don't see the correlation.
I’m with Henry there. Mimic Vat still has its place, and it’s a space Mirage Mirror doesn’t encroach on.
Mirror doesn't get the ETB, but it's just more versatile and it protects itself.
It gets static effects and attack triggers.
It's just a more tool boxy effect.
I'd almost always rather run Mirror than Vat. Though I run both in Sedris.

It’s more versatile, yes, but I don’t think any of us would disagree with that.
Getting ETB effects is massive, and grave hate isn’t irrelevant.
(you can turn Mirror into Vat and exile something under it.)
I think the versatility is what makes me want to run it generally over Vat. Even though the effects *are* different.
That's the part that's holding me up - are you comparing them because they're 3-drop artifacts?
No, I think the effects are different, but similar.
they overlap in the potential to control an opponent's creature card
sort of
They’re both great but the overlap is fairly minimal imo
Sort of.

I guess. Mirage Mirror is definitely has more uses in a vacuum without debate, but I guess, for me, it’s not pushing Mimic Vat.

The lack of ETB effect is still killer for me.
Same CMC, yes. Also same activation cost, but Mirror is repeatable.
<@U3QMCLQQG> Replied to your tweet. Thanks for the shout out.

Sure, but Mirror makes up for it in versatility since it can become land, enchantment, etc. whereas Vat merely gets creatures. Either way, I still don't see them as being comparable cut considerations for a deck.
If I was looking for a cut in a deck to make room for Mirror, I would definitely put Vat on the chopping block. It might not be the thing I cut, but I'd consider it.
Jeremy, Sad Robot is a good pick.
I just don't see it anymore.
I see it everywhere
Henry, the eternal contrarian.
I know folks are down on it, but the value in non-green decks is too good.
mana fixing, a little ramp and card draw, and most other colors can abuse it since it's on a body.
I do run it in Sedris. It's very good there because I can clone it as well as recur it easily.

Watching Legacy at SCG and I never understand how no one seems to run removal in this format such that DRS just sticks around.
Yes, I know it's banned now, but watching this game it's just silly that DRS is scary because no one can remove a 1/2
Is Fatal Push not a thing in this format?
most of the interaction is FoW
Delver variants will run Bolt and Push, pending colors. Just glancing
DRS is more about inevitability and utility than it is an immediate “must answer” threat. It’s not about being able to remove it, it’s keeping it from doing its thing no matter what
If you kill it, it can't do its thing.
I've never played Legacy and never will, so I get my view is uninformed, but sometimes the best answer is the simplest one.

So, you kill the DRS, but in most decks, if you do that you have to find an answer for the main threat for the deck, Like with delver decks either the young pyro or delver itself become harder to kill

You push the deathrite, but then they untap cast a young pyro and you let it get out of hand for 2 turns before you have a chance to do anything. Which then kills you much faster that’s the deathrite would have
Even beyond a threat assessment standpoint, it’s utility homogenized the format because it is too good at too much
So you don't push DRS and then THAT gets out of hand instead and kills you, so can your deck kill a 2/1 and a bunch of 1/1s or not?
It will not kill you as fast no.
